summary:
Abstract: In this study an analysis of the phonetic adaptation of Arabic and Persian loan-words  in Ottoman Turkish is continued (for the vocalic part of the analysis see Stachowski M. : Some features of the vowel adaptation of Arabic loan-words (along with a few remarks on their consonants) in an Ottoman Turkish dictionary by Arcangelo Carradori (1650) – in: Folia Orientalia 49 (2012): 491-502]). Five phenomena are presented in the context of the general Turkic phonetic  evolution. These are: [a] palatalization of (-)kE- > (-)čE-; [b] varying anlaut nasality: m- >  b- and b- > m-; [c] despirantization of f > p; [d] epenthetic n; [e] shortening of geminates. –– One of the most interesting results of the investigation is a Degemination Resistance Hierarchy (= DRH) of consonantal geminates:
1) The velar stop k (numerous examples);
2) The spirants v, z and non-velar stops b, d (fewer examples);
3) The lateral l (degeminated only in derivatives);
4) The trill r and the nasal stops m (?) and n (no known examples).
 –– The lower the group number (= the DRH index), the more frequent the degemination.
